[MultiSheet] Show scroll bar on sheets navbar when needed

When you have a lot of sheets, or a small screen, you can't easily
navigate between sheets since the first or the last sheet buttons are
hidden.

This adds overflow-x auto, and increases the height of the sheet navbar
to nicely display the scrollbar when needed.

Avoid race condition due to yield, abandon waiting on CmdExtension.

The swapping of parseobj in ScheduleSheetCommands will interfer with the
yielding of CPU time if sci.maxtimeslice is exceeded.  This can cause
commands to get executed twice.  To avoid this, I'm now passing the parseobj
around in all function invocations, and the saveundo as well.  That way I
won't have to rely on some state which might be subject to change.

Since the ResumeFromCmdExtension only has a single argument, it doesn't fit
in with the new signatures.  As there are no calls to that function in the
whole code base, the function has been removed, along with the related
cmdextensionbusy.  If this machinery is required in some third-party setup,
then its use should be documented and preferably changed.  It might be best
if any command extension accepts a single callback as an argument and calls
that if it wants to resume operations, without having to worry about what
parameters to pass.  That way, the code invocing the extension could take
care of wrapping all required arguments in a suitable closure.

Make closure compiler a variable in the Makefile.

This way, users can pass different things as the command to invoke the
closure compiler.  For example, "java -jar /path/to/compiler.jar" or
something like that.

Introduced CLOSURE_ARGS parameter so users can pass additional arguments to
the closure compiler, e.g.
CLOSURE_ARGS="-O=WHITESPACE_ONLY --formatting=PRETTY_PRINT"
to get a human-readable version of the almost unmodified input for debugging.

Got rid of unneccessary perl invocation.  We don't need --js in front of
every single file; once for the whole set is enough.  (Even if we wanted it
for every file, we still could do so without perl).

Dropped the double colon from the rule.  There appears to be no need for
such an obscure feature here.  The other double-colon rules are still in
place, though.
